  "footnotes": [
    "Kingdom of Saba (c.1200–275 BCE): the biblical Sheba; centered on Ma'rib and its great dam (one of the engineering wonders of the ancient world); Sabaean inscriptions are among the earliest South Semitic texts; the Ma'rib Dam's final collapse (c.570 CE) became a symbol of civilizational decline in Islamic tradition",
    "Himyarite Kingdom (c.110 BCE–525 CE): unified all of Yemen under one crown; uniquely, the late Himyarite kings adopted Judaism (Yathar/Yusuf dynasty); the persecution of Christians at Najran provoked Aksumite Ethiopia's invasion in 525; the Himyarite era represents the last indigenous Yemeni great power",
    "Incense trade: ancient Yemen's wealth rested on the frankincense and myrrh trade — aromatics essential to religious rituals across the ancient Mediterranean and Near East; the 'Incense Road' connected Hadramaut to Gaza and Petra; Roman demand made South Arabia one of the wealthiest regions in the ancient world (Arabia Felix — 'Fortunate Arabia')",
    "Zaidi Imamate (897–1962): the longest-lasting state in Yemeni history; Zaidi Shia imams ruled the northern highlands almost continuously for over a millennium; their theological tradition emphasizes the imam as both spiritual and temporal leader from the Prophet's family; the Houthi movement draws on this Zaidi heritage",
    "Rasulid dynasty (1229–1454): widely considered the golden age of medieval Yemen; the Rasulids patronized architecture, scholarship, and agriculture; they compiled encyclopedic works on astronomy, agriculture, and medicine; Aden flourished as an Indian Ocean entrepôt",
    "British Aden (1839–1967): Britain seized Aden as a coaling station on the route to India; it became one of the world's busiest ports; the hinterland was organized into the Aden Protectorate with dozens of minor sultanates; independence in 1967 produced the only Marxist state in the Arab world",
    "Yemeni Civil War (2014–): the Houthi movement (Ansar Allah — Zaidi revivalist) seized Sana'a in 2014; Saudi Arabia and the UAE intervened militarily in 2015; the war has created what the UN called 'the world's worst humanitarian crisis' with over 150,000 dead and millions displaced"
  ]
